Here's a JavaScript code that can find an object by its name deep inside a given object, without using recursion and returning the path used to reach the object:

```
function findObject(obj, name, path) {
  if (obj === null || obj === undefined) {
    return null;
  }
  if (obj[name] !== undefined) {
    return {obj: obj[name], path: path + '.' + name};
  }
  for (var key in obj) {
    if (obj[key] !== null && obj[key] !== undefined) {
      var result = findObject(obj[key], name, path + '.' + key);
      if (result !== null) {
        return result;
      }
    }
  }
  return null;
}
```

To use this function, you can call it with the object you want to search, the name of the object you want to find, and an empty string as the initial path. Here's an example:

