```
class Shape:
    def __init__(self, color):
        self.color = color

    def draw(self):
        print(f"Drawing a {self.color} shape.")


class Circle(Shape):
    def __init__(self, color, radius):
        super().__init__(color)
        self.radius = radius

    def draw(self):
        print(f"Drawing a {self.color} circle with radius {self.radius}.")
```

In this implementation, the Circle class inherits from the Shape class. The Circle class has an additional attribute, `radius`, which is passed in during initialization.

The `draw` method in the Circle class overrides the `draw` method in the Shape class. This allows the Circle class to provide its own implementation of the `draw` method.

Here's an example of a blocking read that is interrupted by a signal, with EINTR handling:

```
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <signal.h>
#include <errno.h>

void handle_signal(int sig) {
    printf("Caught signal %d\n", sig);
}

int main() {
    int fd = open("file.txt", O_RDONLY);
    if (fd == -1) {
        perror("open");
        exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
    }

    // Set up signal handler
    signal(SIGINT, handle_signal);

    // Perform blocking read
    char buffer[1024];
    ssize_t bytes_read = read(fd, buffer, sizeof(buffer)));
    if (bytes_read == -1) {
        if (errno == EINTR) {
            printf("Read interrupted by signal\n");
        } else {
            perror("read");
            exit(EXIT_FAILURE);
        }
    }

    // Close file descriptor
    close(fd);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we open a file for reading, set up a signal handler for SIGINT, and perform a blocking read on the file descriptor. If the read is interrupted by a signal, we check the value of `errno` to determine if the interrupt was caused by a signal. If it was, we print a message indicating that the read was interrupted by a signal.

