To ensure that the memory region at virtual address 0x100000 is mapped, you can use the `ioremap()` function in your kernel module.

Here's an example of how to use `ioremap()` to map the memory region at virtual address 0x100000:

```
#include <linux/module.h>
#include <linux/kernel.h>
#include <linux/io.h>

#define MY_ADDR 0x100000
#define MY_SIZE 0x1000

static void __iomem *my_addr;

static int __init my_module_init(void)
{
    my_addr = ioremap(MY_ADDR, MY_SIZE);
    if (!my_addr) {
        printk(KERN_ERR "Failed to map memory region at virtual address 0x%x\n", MY_ADDR));
        return -ENOMEM;
    }
    printk(KERN_INFO "Memory region at virtual address 0x%x mapped successfully\n", MY_ADDR));
    return 0;
}

static void __exit my_module_exit(void)
{
    if (my_addr) {
        iounmap(my_addr);
        printk(KERN_INFO "Memory region at virtual address 0x%x unmapped successfully\n", MY_ADDR));
    }
}

module_init(my_module_init);
module_exit(my_module_exit);

MODULE_LICENSE("GPL");
MODULE_AUTHOR("Your Name");
MODULE_DESCRIPTION("A Linux kernel module that maps a memory region at virtual address 0x100000");
```

In this example, we define the virtual address and size of the memory region that we want to map. We then use the `ioremap()` function to map the memory region at the specified virtual address. Finally, we use the `iounmap()` function to unmap the memory region when the module is unloaded.

