We then define three concrete strategies that implement the `TransactionStrategy` interface: `DepositStrategy`, `WithdrawalStrategy`, and `TransferStrategy`.

Each of these strategies implements the `executeTransaction` method, which logs a message to the console indicating the type of transaction being executed and the amount involved.

We then define a context class `BankingApp` that uses the strategy pattern. This class has a private field `transactionStrategy` of type `TransactionStrategy`.

The `BankingApp` class has a constructor that takes a `transactionStrategy` parameter of type `TransactionStrategy`. This constructor initializes the `transactionStrategy` field of the `BankingApp` class.

The `BankingApp` class has a public method `executeTransaction` that takes an `amount` parameter of type `number` and returns `void`. This method simply calls the `executeTransaction` method of the `transactionStrategy` field of the `BankingApp` class, passing in the `amount` parameter.

Finally, we use the `BankingApp` class with different transaction strategies. We create three instances of the `TransactionStrategy` interface: `depositStrategy`, `withdrawalStrategy`, and `transferStrategy`. We then create an instance of the `BankingApp` class, passing in the `depositStrategy` instance as the `transactionStrategy` parameter. We then call the `executeTransaction` method of the `BankingApp` instance, passing in the `100` value as the `amount` parameter. This logs a message to the console indicating that a deposit of `100` has been executed. We then change the `transactionStrategy` field of the `BankingApp` instance to the `withdrawalStrategy` instance. We then call the `executeTransaction` method of the `BankingApp` instance, passing in the `50` value as the `amount` parameter. This logs a message to the console indicating that a withdrawal of `50` has been executed. Finally, we change the `transactionStrategy` field of the `BankingApp` instance to the `transferStrategy` instance. We then call the `executeTransaction` method of the `BankingApp` instance, passing in the `200` value as the `amount` parameter. This logs a message to the console indicating that a transfer of `200` has been executed.

